The paper deals with a scheduling problem involving machines and jobs, which is a classic topic in computer science. The use of cloud machines and the consideration of machine-type dependent prices and setup times suggest that the paper may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or Information Theory (cs.IT) categories. The study of competitiveness and the development of an online algorithm suggest that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Computational Complexity (cs.CC) categories. Finally, the consideration of slack as a parameter suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category.
